1
00:00:45,504 --> 00:00:46,838
It's incredible.

2
00:00:46,839 --> 00:00:48,422
It's not finished.

3
00:00:48,423 --> 00:00:50,592
- Go away.
- [chuckles]

4
00:00:53,095 --> 00:00:54,512
How's it feel painting again?

5
00:00:54,513 --> 00:00:57,266
Mmm. It's pretty wobbly.

6
00:00:58,642 --> 00:01:01,687
Have you given any more thought to
what we talked about the other night?

7
00:01:03,355 --> 00:01:04,396
What?

8
00:01:04,397 --> 00:01:05,690
Quitting the gallery.

9
00:01:05,691 --> 00:01:07,358
Painting full-time.

10
00:01:07,359 --> 00:01:09,360
[both chuckle]

11
00:01:09,361 --> 00:01:12,864
You... You better be
careful what you ask for.

12
00:01:12,865 --> 00:01:15,366
You're liable to wind up
with a house full of these.

13
00:01:15,367 --> 00:01:18,661
You are just too good to be
curating other people's work.

14
00:01:18,662 --> 00:01:20,372
- Seriously.
- [sighs]

15
00:01:21,248 --> 00:01:24,293
Well, let's see what
happens with the deal.

16
00:01:25,919 --> 00:01:26,920
The deal...

17
00:01:29,381 --> 00:01:30,424
is done.

18
00:01:36,638 --> 00:01:38,598
These numbers don't
even make sense.

19
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:39,974
- [chuckles]
- [stammers]

20
00:01:39,975 --> 00:01:41,350
[footsteps approaching]

21
00:01:41,351 --> 00:01:42,435
[chuckles]

22
00:01:42,436 --> 00:01:45,104
Hey, uh, can I get a ride?

23
00:01:45,105 --> 00:01:47,273
- [Daniela] Where do you want to go?
- Skate park.

24
00:01:47,274 --> 00:01:48,941
Yeah, I'll take you.

25
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:51,320
No, I'll do it. Let me.

26
00:01:52,404 --> 00:01:54,615
I have an errand
anyway. I'll take you.

27
00:01:55,490 --> 00:01:56,909
You gonna meet Brooke?

28
00:01:58,452 --> 00:02:01,580
- Yeah.
- Mmm. Is this the date?

29
00:02:02,247 --> 00:02:03,664
I mean, I could just walk.

30
00:02:03,665 --> 00:02:07,294
Ah, relax. I won't embarrass
you. Come on. Grab your things.

31
00:02:09,838 --> 00:02:11,215
Keep painting.

32
00:02:24,895 --> 00:02:26,146
You a little nervous?

33
00:02:28,023 --> 00:02:29,399
Yeah, little bit.

34
00:02:31,818 --> 00:02:33,028
That's good.

35
00:02:33,779 --> 00:02:35,363
That's not a bad
thing, you know?

36
00:02:35,364 --> 00:02:37,032
Nerves keep you sharp.

37
00:02:38,283 --> 00:02:39,409
Yeah.

38
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,873
[chattering]

39
00:02:52,798 --> 00:02:55,050
Have fun, pal. You got this.

40
00:03:00,097 --> 00:03:02,432
- Hey.
- Hey. How's it going?

41
00:03:15,946 --> 00:03:16,947
Well...

42
00:03:18,282 --> 00:03:20,200
you look ready for an adventure.

43
00:03:20,784 --> 00:03:21,784
[laughs]

44
00:03:21,785 --> 00:03:22,953
Oh, you like that?

45
00:03:23,495 --> 00:03:24,955
It's a vibe, right?

46
00:03:25,998 --> 00:03:27,249
That for me?

47
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:30,335
- There you go.
- [gasping]

48
00:03:32,588 --> 00:03:35,298
Oh, and I'll text you my
guy, all right. He's good.

49
00:03:35,299 --> 00:03:37,092
Got me out of a
jam a time or two.

50
00:03:39,136 --> 00:03:40,679
Oh, wow.

51
00:03:42,514 --> 00:03:44,474
Sure you wanna seal off the box?

52
00:03:45,767 --> 00:03:46,767
Mmm.

53
00:03:46,768 --> 00:03:47,853
Yeah?

54
00:03:51,231 --> 00:03:52,858
Why'd you really come back, huh?

55
00:03:55,694 --> 00:03:57,154
It was for her, wasn't it?

56
00:03:58,280 --> 00:03:59,323
Yeah.

57
00:04:00,824 --> 00:04:02,701
That's what you fucked
up in your world.

58
00:04:03,744 --> 00:04:06,663
Built this instead of
making a life with her.

59
00:04:09,458 --> 00:04:10,501
Am I close?

60
00:04:15,088 --> 00:04:16,298
Safe travels.

61
00:04:16,964 --> 00:04:18,759
Remember everything
I've told you.

62
00:04:19,801 --> 00:04:21,887
I really hope you find
what you're looking for.

63
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:27,809
[groans]

64
00:04:34,483 --> 00:04:35,567
[strains]

65
00:04:51,583 --> 00:04:52,626
See you, guys.

66
00:04:57,631 --> 00:04:59,675
- Walk with me? Let's go.
- Yeah.

67
00:05:01,927 --> 00:05:02,928
[sighs]

68
00:05:07,599 --> 00:05:08,934
[sighs]

69
00:05:14,314 --> 00:05:15,524
I, uh...

70
00:05:19,444 --> 00:05:20,946
I bought you something.

71
00:05:23,407 --> 00:05:24,491
You're late.

72
00:05:25,075 --> 00:05:26,076
Yep.

73
00:05:29,454 --> 00:05:32,958
Kind of ornery for a guy who just
spent time with the girl he likes.

74
00:05:34,710 --> 00:05:36,627
Drew was there. Fucked me again.

75
00:05:36,628 --> 00:05:37,713
Oh.

76
00:05:38,297 --> 00:05:40,757
You know what? You're gonna
have to do something about that.

77
00:05:42,092 --> 00:05:43,093
Like what?

78
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:47,138
I don't know. It's
for you to figure out.

79
00:05:47,139 --> 00:05:49,348
If you don't try something...

80
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:50,975
Yeah, well, that's
easier said than...

81
00:05:50,976 --> 00:05:53,227
Yeah, well, you know,
you're gonna regret it.

82
00:05:53,228 --> 00:05:56,022
And regret will eat you
up inside, that's all.

83
00:05:56,023 --> 00:05:58,317
- [clears throat, coughs]
- What?

84
00:05:59,109 --> 00:06:02,070
[clearing throat, choking]

85
00:06:03,197 --> 00:06:04,823
What's going on? Charlie?

86
00:06:05,449 --> 00:06:07,200
- Is that... Oh, God. Is that...
- Fuck.

87
00:06:07,201 --> 00:06:08,201
[tires squealing]

88
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:10,203
- [Jason] Allergy?
- Yeah.

89
00:06:10,204 --> 00:06:11,871
[gasping, choking]

90
00:06:11,872 --> 00:06:12,915
What is it?

91
00:06:13,832 --> 00:06:14,832
Bag?

92
00:06:14,833 --> 00:06:16,334
- I got it. I got it.
- [gasping]

93
00:06:16,335 --> 00:06:18,545
[stammers] What
am I looking for?

94
00:06:19,213 --> 00:06:20,630
- An EpiPen?
- [gasping]

95
00:06:20,631 --> 00:06:23,007
Come on! What does it look like?

96
00:06:23,008 --> 00:06:24,218
Fuck.

97
00:06:25,219 --> 00:06:28,596
This? Hold on. Hold
on. Oh, my God.

98
00:06:28,597 --> 00:06:31,225
Now what do I do,
huh? Come on. Okay.

99
00:06:44,029 --> 00:06:45,655
Hey. He's fine, right?

100
00:06:45,656 --> 00:06:47,407
- Yeah, he's gonna be fine.
- Okay.

101
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:50,118
They're just checking him.

102
00:06:50,827 --> 00:06:52,245
[sighs] You okay?

103
00:06:52,246 --> 00:06:53,330
Yeah.

104
00:06:53,914 --> 00:06:56,499
[sighs] How'd it happen?

105
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,959
[sighs] It's my fault.

106
00:06:57,960 --> 00:06:59,920
I... I gave him ice cream.

107
00:07:00,671 --> 00:07:01,755
What do you mean?

108
00:07:02,464 --> 00:07:04,257
It had nuts in it.

109
00:07:04,258 --> 00:07:06,343
I... I didn't read the...

110
00:07:06,927 --> 00:07:08,428
I wasn't thinking.

111
00:07:09,054 --> 00:07:12,891
How much thinking has to happen
to remember he has an allergy?

112
00:07:15,644 --> 00:07:16,645
I know.

113
00:07:20,774 --> 00:07:21,774
[sighs]

114
00:08:09,781 --> 00:08:11,950
[clicking tongue]

115
00:08:19,082 --> 00:08:20,542
What are you doing?

116
00:08:22,044 --> 00:08:26,381
Mmm. Have to get the gallery
space assigned for the auction.

117
00:08:27,049 --> 00:08:28,759
So busy.

118
00:08:31,011 --> 00:08:32,054
Mm-hmm.

119
00:08:35,724 --> 00:08:41,355
I called dibs on not working the event,
so they dumped all the prep work on me.

120
00:08:49,947 --> 00:08:50,947
[sighs]

121
00:08:52,115 --> 00:08:53,867
Can I help you with something?

122
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:01,667
Nope. [sighs]

123
00:09:04,127 --> 00:09:05,128
[grunts]

124
00:09:08,090 --> 00:09:09,299
Hey.

125
00:09:14,847 --> 00:09:16,682
Since when did you
start flossing?

126
00:09:18,725 --> 00:09:20,310
I always floss.

127
00:09:22,813 --> 00:09:25,731
You floss the day you have a dental
appointment and it fools no one.

128
00:09:25,732 --> 00:09:26,941
[inhales deeply]

129
00:09:26,942 --> 00:09:29,610
Well, I decided to give a
shit about my gum health.

130
00:09:29,611 --> 00:09:31,154
Is... Is that a problem?

131
00:09:32,364 --> 00:09:35,117
No, just a curiosity.

132
00:09:36,285 --> 00:09:38,495
Mmm. Okay.

133
00:09:40,205 --> 00:09:42,416
[breathes deeply]

134
00:11:07,668 --> 00:11:09,753
[birds chirping]

135
00:11:25,853 --> 00:11:27,478
How is it going?

136
00:11:27,479 --> 00:11:29,273
[inhales sharply] Getting there.

137
00:11:52,754 --> 00:11:53,839
[Jason groans]

138
00:12:24,328 --> 00:12:26,079
- Fuck.
- What?

139
00:12:50,437 --> 00:12:52,271
- What?
- Door is red.

140
00:12:52,272 --> 00:12:53,815
- [dog barking]
- [door opens]

141
00:12:58,320 --> 00:12:59,488
[Jason sighs]

142
00:13:00,614 --> 00:13:02,115
That's not my wife...

143
00:13:03,825 --> 00:13:05,035
and not my dog.

144
00:13:05,577 --> 00:13:07,995
It's not my door,
it's not my house.

145
00:13:07,996 --> 00:13:10,415
It's not my fucking day.

146
00:13:31,019 --> 00:13:32,896
I don't think anybody's home.

147
00:13:34,857 --> 00:13:38,277
But it doesn't matter 'cause the
remembrance tree is not there.

148
00:13:40,529 --> 00:13:42,114
[groans] Man.

149
00:13:43,991 --> 00:13:47,035
You know, this is worse
than all those crazy worlds.

150
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:50,956
A bunch of Chicagos that
are not quite right.

151
00:13:52,541 --> 00:13:56,712
Almost, but none
of them are mine.

152
00:14:00,757 --> 00:14:03,551
I don't know that I'm ready
to go back to the box.

153
00:14:03,552 --> 00:14:04,720
Me neither.

154
00:14:05,929 --> 00:14:08,348
We're getting a real
place to sleep tonight.

155
00:14:27,618 --> 00:14:28,702
[grunts]

156
00:14:31,413 --> 00:14:32,705
[Amanda] This is amazing.

157
00:14:32,706 --> 00:14:33,832
Mmm.

158
00:14:36,168 --> 00:14:37,335
Oh, my God.

159
00:14:37,336 --> 00:14:40,421
I'm not sure if it's hunger
or if it's really this good.

160
00:14:40,422 --> 00:14:42,299
- It's really this good.
- It is, right?

161
00:14:44,468 --> 00:14:46,595
Oh, yeah. Hey, well...

162
00:14:48,305 --> 00:14:51,225
You didn't say, did you
find this world's Amanda?

163
00:14:52,976 --> 00:14:54,686
She's not a therapist.

164
00:14:55,312 --> 00:14:56,562
Really?

165
00:14:56,563 --> 00:14:58,272
Ready for this?

166
00:14:58,273 --> 00:14:59,357
Mmm.

167
00:14:59,358 --> 00:15:01,484
She manages a White Castle.

168
00:15:01,485 --> 00:15:04,445
- No. No.
- [laughs]

169
00:15:04,446 --> 00:15:06,156
At least you're a manager.

170
00:15:08,367 --> 00:15:10,786
Do you ever wonder how, I...

171
00:15:11,328 --> 00:15:15,998
If you strip back the
trappings, um, like lifestyle

172
00:15:15,999 --> 00:15:18,334
and all the external things,

173
00:15:18,335 --> 00:15:20,837
what are the key components

174
00:15:20,838 --> 00:15:25,217
at... at... at your
core that make you you?

175
00:15:26,009 --> 00:15:27,177
You mean I'm still her,

176
00:15:28,011 --> 00:15:31,013
White Castle Amanda, at
the most fundamental level?

177
00:15:31,014 --> 00:15:33,015
- Yeah. [laughs]
- [laughing]

178
00:15:33,016 --> 00:15:34,101
Exactly.

179
00:15:35,811 --> 00:15:36,978
Well... [sighs]

180
00:15:36,979 --> 00:15:41,232
personality is just, uh... it's
a pattern of thoughts, feelings,

181
00:15:41,233 --> 00:15:43,151
behaviors unique to each person.

182
00:15:44,278 --> 00:15:47,029
We like to think of it
as fixed, but it's not.

183
00:15:47,030 --> 00:15:49,699
- Yeah, I think people change...
- It's actually not.

184
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:52,411
but the essentials
stay the same.

185
00:15:53,036 --> 00:15:56,957
Yeah, sure. Our temperament
gets locked around age three,

186
00:15:57,583 --> 00:16:02,086
but that's just the intensity of our
reaction to the environment we're in.

187
00:16:02,087 --> 00:16:05,674
For example, my Jason, he
struggled with his temper.

188
00:16:06,675 --> 00:16:07,967
- Same.
- That's what I thought.

189
00:16:07,968 --> 00:16:12,180
But you are more empathetic and in
control of your impulses than he ever was.

190
00:16:12,181 --> 00:16:15,057
And that's because of your
experiences, your choices.

191
00:16:15,058 --> 00:16:18,769
Our personality changes a lot
during our lifetime and it's...

192
00:16:18,770 --> 00:16:20,980
["Raspberry Beret" playing]

193
00:16:20,981 --> 00:16:22,858
I love this song.

194
00:16:25,819 --> 00:16:27,070
What?

195
00:16:28,780 --> 00:16:31,115
No. [stammers] Come on.

196
00:16:31,116 --> 00:16:33,326
Uh, no, I'm good. I don't dance.

197
00:16:33,327 --> 00:16:35,412
Of course you don't dance.

198
00:16:35,954 --> 00:16:36,954
He didn't either.

199
00:16:38,498 --> 00:16:40,209
What are you afraid of?

200
00:16:41,168 --> 00:16:42,877
What everyone's afraid of.

201
00:16:42,878 --> 00:16:46,672
If you look stupid, you
can leave this restaurant,

202
00:16:46,673 --> 00:16:51,969
you can leave this city, or you
can literally leave this world.

203
00:16:51,970 --> 00:16:53,262
Let's do that.

204
00:16:53,263 --> 00:16:54,181
Fuck it.

205
00:16:54,182 --> 00:16:57,017
[groans]

206
00:17:47,442 --> 00:17:48,694
[horn honks]

207
00:17:49,486 --> 00:17:51,780
[laughing]

208
00:17:54,157 --> 00:17:55,576
[speaks indistinctly]

209
00:17:56,702 --> 00:17:57,702
Uh.

210
00:17:58,412 --> 00:17:59,454
[groans]

211
00:18:01,957 --> 00:18:03,291
[song fades]

212
00:18:03,292 --> 00:18:05,419
[thunder rumbles]

213
00:18:06,712 --> 00:18:09,673
[breathing heavily]

214
00:18:29,985 --> 00:18:31,027
[Jason] Hey.

215
00:18:31,028 --> 00:18:33,280
[groans] Hey.

216
00:18:35,199 --> 00:18:38,869
That was a pretty great night.

217
00:18:40,204 --> 00:18:43,165
[chuckles] Yeah.

218
00:18:44,833 --> 00:18:47,503
Yeah, it was. It's crazy.

219
00:18:51,840 --> 00:18:55,760
I feel like my world
is... is vanishing.

220
00:18:55,761 --> 00:18:57,221
Mmm.

221
00:19:00,390 --> 00:19:06,390
Do you think that, um, you
would ever forget it completely?

222
00:19:07,064 --> 00:19:11,902
I can see getting to a point where
it doesn't feel real anymore.

223
00:19:12,653 --> 00:19:13,820
What do you mean?

224
00:19:15,906 --> 00:19:16,990
Because it's not.

225
00:19:18,617 --> 00:19:23,121
[breathes shakily] This
reality, it's all we have.

226
00:19:26,708 --> 00:19:28,502
[breathes deeply]

227
00:19:34,091 --> 00:19:38,846
If you want me to go to the
other bed, just tell me.

228
00:19:41,473 --> 00:19:44,100
[Jason breathes deeply]

229
00:19:44,101 --> 00:19:45,394
I don't want you to.

230
00:19:49,773 --> 00:19:52,149
I just think that I need you to.

231
00:19:52,150 --> 00:19:53,819
Of course.

232
00:20:00,576 --> 00:20:02,286
[exhales deeply]

233
00:20:13,088 --> 00:20:14,298
[door opens]

234
00:20:14,840 --> 00:20:17,217
[Amanda] Jason, come in.

235
00:20:17,885 --> 00:20:21,138
I have everything
I want. Everything.

236
00:20:22,681 --> 00:20:25,934
But I'm here, talking to
you, because, I guess,

237
00:20:26,935 --> 00:20:31,523
it's not everything I imagined.

238
00:20:34,151 --> 00:20:40,151
And trust me, I've worked so hard
to get these things, to get here.

239
00:20:43,785 --> 00:20:47,497
Do you think it's possible
you built it up too much?

240
00:20:48,957 --> 00:20:52,002
Idealized what this time
in your life might be like?

241
00:20:52,669 --> 00:20:53,878
Hmm.

242
00:20:53,879 --> 00:20:55,671
Maybe you always dreamed about

243
00:20:55,672 --> 00:20:59,009
how amazing it would feel
to have all the things:

244
00:21:00,594 --> 00:21:02,846
a wife you love, a son,

245
00:21:03,847 --> 00:21:05,974
the freedom to do
whatever you want.

246
00:21:06,808 --> 00:21:08,393
But you forgot something.

247
00:21:09,353 --> 00:21:11,146
Life is still just life.

248
00:21:12,481 --> 00:21:14,399
You said it's not
what you expected.

249
00:21:15,484 --> 00:21:16,777
What did you expect?

250
00:21:19,238 --> 00:21:24,409
You're gonna think I'm a
dick if I say perfection.

251
00:21:26,912 --> 00:21:29,112
[Daniela] <i>Now he wants me to
quit my job at the gallery.</i>

252
00:21:30,290 --> 00:21:31,332
Are you going to?

253
00:21:31,333 --> 00:21:32,584
[sighs]

254
00:21:33,418 --> 00:21:37,422
Honestly, I can't really wrap
my head around it all yet.

255
00:21:38,006 --> 00:21:39,257
But it's a lot of money.

256
00:21:39,258 --> 00:21:40,716
- Insane.
- Okay.

257
00:21:40,717 --> 00:21:45,555
Yeah, but there's all
this small stuff too,

258
00:21:45,556 --> 00:21:51,060
like suddenly he flosses every
day, and he dresses better.

259
00:21:51,061 --> 00:21:52,353
Go hire a divorce lawyer.

260
00:21:52,354 --> 00:21:54,105
- [gasps]
- I know they're tiny things.

261
00:21:54,106 --> 00:21:56,941
- There are just so many of them.
- Keep going.

262
00:21:56,942 --> 00:21:59,944
Like, he leaves his keys
on the kitchen counter

263
00:21:59,945 --> 00:22:01,821
instead of hanging them on
the hook by the front door.

264
00:22:01,822 --> 00:22:04,991
He takes his shoes off as
soon as he walks in the door.

265
00:22:04,992 --> 00:22:07,494
He unloads the dishwasher
as soon as it's done.

266
00:22:08,287 --> 00:22:10,246
He wants to have
sex all the time.

267
00:22:10,247 --> 00:22:14,751
Please stop. I'm hearing he's
hotter, cleaner and richer.

268
00:22:17,838 --> 00:22:21,632
That thing with Charlie
though, that's not small.

269
00:22:21,633 --> 00:22:24,428
So, I messed up pretty
bad a few days ago.

270
00:22:25,762 --> 00:22:29,516
I gave my son,
Charlie, ice cream.

271
00:22:30,392 --> 00:22:34,187
It had nuts in it and he had
to go to the emergency room.

272
00:22:34,188 --> 00:22:35,313
Is he okay?

273
00:22:35,314 --> 00:22:36,565
Yeah.

274
00:22:37,482 --> 00:22:38,483
Yeah.

275
00:22:39,234 --> 00:22:40,569
And I'll make it up to him.

276
00:22:41,486 --> 00:22:44,364
But Daniela, you know,
she's still very upset.

277
00:22:46,116 --> 00:22:47,951
- You apologized?
- Yeah.

278
00:22:48,911 --> 00:22:53,206
Yeah, but... [stammers] I feel
like I need to show her that,

279
00:22:53,207 --> 00:22:57,127
you know, I'm paying
attention somehow.

280
00:22:58,670 --> 00:22:59,713
What are you thinking?

281
00:23:01,798 --> 00:23:04,425
I like the big romantic gesture.

282
00:23:04,426 --> 00:23:05,551
Does she?

283
00:23:05,552 --> 00:23:06,929
Don't you?

284
00:23:07,513 --> 00:23:08,639
Doesn't everyone?

285
00:23:09,139 --> 00:23:12,726
My partner and I can have sometimes
different ideas of what's romantic.

286
00:23:13,435 --> 00:23:14,561
Oh, you're married.

287
00:23:15,979 --> 00:23:20,442
The other night, when we were waiting
for Charlie in the emergency room,

288
00:23:22,402 --> 00:23:24,488
I saw these marks on his arm.

289
00:23:25,072 --> 00:23:26,072
Like an injury?

290
00:23:26,740 --> 00:23:27,907
Like needle marks.

291
00:23:27,908 --> 00:23:29,243
Like track marks?

292
00:23:32,454 --> 00:23:34,081
You really buried the lede.

293
00:23:36,041 --> 00:23:38,335
- Did you ask him?
- No.

294
00:23:39,127 --> 00:23:43,005
And he's been out all the
time at night recently.

295
00:23:43,006 --> 00:23:46,677
He says that it's for these
sales meetings, but I don't know.

296
00:23:49,096 --> 00:23:50,137
I should talk to him.

297
00:23:50,138 --> 00:23:51,723
No, don't.

298
00:23:52,474 --> 00:23:55,102
No, he'll lie and
you'll tip him off.

299
00:23:56,603 --> 00:23:57,604
You need to follow him.

300
00:23:59,606 --> 00:24:00,858
- Really?
- Yes.

301
00:24:01,608 --> 00:24:03,401
Find out what's really going on.

302
00:24:03,402 --> 00:24:04,486
[scoffs]

303
00:24:06,154 --> 00:24:07,155
No.

304
00:24:08,407 --> 00:24:09,783
I'll talk to him.

305
00:24:12,369 --> 00:24:14,162
By the way, how did
you hear about me?

306
00:24:16,373 --> 00:24:17,791
An ex-girlfriend.

307
00:24:18,750 --> 00:24:20,002
It's a long story.

308
00:24:31,221 --> 00:24:32,222
Hey.

309
00:24:33,807 --> 00:24:35,267
I was hoping we could talk.

310
00:24:36,351 --> 00:24:39,437
I would love that,
but I'm headed out.

311
00:24:39,438 --> 00:24:41,063
Where you going?

312
00:24:41,064 --> 00:24:42,357
Where are we going?

313
00:24:43,734 --> 00:24:48,488
That's for me to know,
and you to find out.

314
00:24:55,704 --> 00:24:58,206
[chuckles] Is there
dinner involved in this?

315
00:24:58,207 --> 00:25:00,416
- Yes, yes.
- [chuckles] Okay.

316
00:25:00,417 --> 00:25:04,129
But first, we just need
to pop in somewhere.

317
00:25:04,880 --> 00:25:08,550
There's just one
quick stop first.

318
00:25:09,092 --> 00:25:10,302
We are here.

319
00:25:16,600 --> 00:25:18,810
You brought me to
the charity auction?

320
00:25:19,436 --> 00:25:20,937
- Yes.
- [chuckles] No.

321
00:25:20,938 --> 00:25:25,066
No, I just want to sh... One thing. I
want you to see one thing really quick.

322
00:25:25,067 --> 00:25:26,652
- I don't understand.
- Come on.

323
00:25:27,861 --> 00:25:30,405
[attendees chattering]

324
00:25:46,255 --> 00:25:47,255
Why are we here?

325
00:25:47,256 --> 00:25:48,841
Trust me. Just trust me.

326
00:25:54,054 --> 00:25:56,347
Hi. How are you?
Nice to see you. Hi.

327
00:25:56,348 --> 00:25:57,474
[attendee] Good to see you.

328
00:26:02,062 --> 00:26:05,566
- Okay. Right behind you.
- What is?

329
00:26:16,159 --> 00:26:17,994
- Take me home.
- What's the matter?

330
00:26:17,995 --> 00:26:19,079
I wanna go home.

331
00:26:27,713 --> 00:26:31,966
Okay, listen, I know...
I know that I messed up.

332
00:26:31,967 --> 00:26:34,845
I... I seriously don't know how.

333
00:26:35,679 --> 00:26:36,721
You don't get how?

334
00:26:36,722 --> 00:26:38,431
No. I thought you
would be happy.

335
00:26:38,432 --> 00:26:39,640
[scoffs]

336
00:26:39,641 --> 00:26:41,101
- Yeah.
- [sighs]

337
00:26:41,977 --> 00:26:42,978
No.

338
00:26:43,854 --> 00:26:45,188
No, I'm not happy.

339
00:26:45,189 --> 00:26:49,775
[breathes shakily] I'm really,
really fucking humiliated.

340
00:26:49,776 --> 00:26:53,029
Humiliat... The
painting is great.

341
00:26:53,030 --> 00:26:59,030
And you took it without my permission,
and you asked my colleagues to hang it.

342
00:26:59,203 --> 00:27:00,578
They were happy to
hang it. They...

343
00:27:00,579 --> 00:27:03,081
They had no choice
but to hang it.

344
00:27:04,333 --> 00:27:07,460
And then you put me in
this dress that I hate,

345
00:27:07,461 --> 00:27:11,340
and you took me there
where everyone knows me.

346
00:27:11,840 --> 00:27:13,967
And not only was
that painting bad,

347
00:27:14,635 --> 00:27:16,636
it wasn't even finished.

348
00:27:16,637 --> 00:27:17,929
That painting is good.

349
00:27:17,930 --> 00:27:21,182
- It's great. It's great!
- That is not your decision, Jason.

350
00:27:21,183 --> 00:27:22,809
It is my work.

351
00:27:24,228 --> 00:27:25,436
And it's private.

352
00:27:25,437 --> 00:27:27,396
And I told you that I
didn't want to sell it.

353
00:27:27,397 --> 00:27:30,066
All right, so don't sell
it! Don't fucking sell it.

354
00:27:30,067 --> 00:27:33,194
Just... I don't see why
people can't see it.

355
00:27:33,195 --> 00:27:35,864
Because I haven't
painted in years!

356
00:27:37,282 --> 00:27:40,744
Because I'm still trying to figure
out if I even want to anymore!

357
00:27:42,704 --> 00:27:45,039
How could you even
think it would be okay?

358
00:27:45,040 --> 00:27:49,752
Maybe, uh, you're just not
the person I thought you were.

359
00:27:49,753 --> 00:27:50,754
[stammers]

360
00:27:52,172 --> 00:27:54,215
I didn't mean that like that.

361
00:27:54,216 --> 00:27:55,300
I didn't...

362
00:27:58,011 --> 00:27:59,096
Maybe I'm not.

363
00:28:02,474 --> 00:28:04,058
I just want you to be happy.

364
00:28:04,059 --> 00:28:05,853
Please. You want
you to be happy.

365
00:29:25,766 --> 00:29:27,518
[breathing heavily]

366
00:29:35,943 --> 00:29:39,905
- [door opens, closes]
- [breathes shakily]

367
00:30:46,638 --> 00:30:47,638
[grunts]

368
00:30:57,482 --> 00:30:58,692
[object bangs]

369
00:31:25,260 --> 00:31:26,803
What is this?

370
00:31:27,763 --> 00:31:29,640
I think he's been injecting it.

371
00:31:30,599 --> 00:31:32,476
What? You mean, like, drugs? No.

372
00:31:33,101 --> 00:31:34,228
He has marks.

373
00:31:37,523 --> 00:31:38,524
Shit.

374
00:31:40,609 --> 00:31:42,026
Um, okay, wait.

375
00:31:42,027 --> 00:31:45,738
Maybe he's sick and
doesn't want to worry you.

376
00:31:45,739 --> 00:31:47,615
He's trying out some
experimental drug.

377
00:31:47,616 --> 00:31:50,202
I think secret
illness is a reach.

378
00:31:52,037 --> 00:31:54,413
Although he has a storage unit
that he didn't tell me about.

379
00:31:54,414 --> 00:31:56,166
- Really? What's in that?
- That.

380
00:31:57,334 --> 00:31:59,169
I don't know what else.
I couldn't get in.

381
00:32:00,254 --> 00:32:01,255
[sniffs]

382
00:32:01,839 --> 00:32:03,423
Can you sequence it?

383
00:32:06,552 --> 00:32:08,720
It's not much of a
sample, but, yeah.

384
00:32:11,056 --> 00:32:15,727
Maybe just find out what it is,
and then we figure out what to do.

385
00:32:30,075 --> 00:32:31,159
[door closes]

386
00:32:33,954 --> 00:32:35,163
Are you okay?

387
00:32:37,916 --> 00:32:38,917
Yeah.

388
00:32:40,711 --> 00:32:44,964
Just think I need
a day for myself.

389
00:32:44,965 --> 00:32:46,800
Can we meet back here tonight?

390
00:32:49,636 --> 00:32:52,306
And what if this is my world?

391
00:32:53,765 --> 00:32:56,435
Either way, meet
me here tonight?

392
00:33:30,761 --> 00:33:32,346
[footsteps approaching]

393
00:33:33,055 --> 00:33:34,056
Can I help you?

394
00:33:39,102 --> 00:33:40,896
Are you the artist?

395
00:33:43,941 --> 00:33:45,400
It's, uh, amazing.

396
00:33:46,068 --> 00:33:47,193
Thanks.

397
00:33:47,194 --> 00:33:48,403
This...

398
00:33:50,072 --> 00:33:54,701
It reminds me of Juneway
Beach, for some reason.

399
00:33:55,911 --> 00:33:56,995
It is.

400
00:33:58,539 --> 00:33:59,540
[chuckles]

401
00:34:00,457 --> 00:34:05,462
Yeah, it's like... it's
like the fall or something.

402
00:34:06,839 --> 00:34:08,257
November, actually.

403
00:34:10,884 --> 00:34:12,176
I like the sunrises.

404
00:34:12,177 --> 00:34:13,344
Yeah.

405
00:34:15,514 --> 00:34:19,015
Well, I'll let you just, um,
walk around. I'll be over here.

406
00:34:19,016 --> 00:34:21,017
If you have any more
questions just let me know.

407
00:34:21,018 --> 00:34:26,149
Um, my... my wife is,
uh... is an artist.

408
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:28,442
Oh.

409
00:34:28,443 --> 00:34:31,196
- Is she local?
- Yeah. Yeah. Well...

410
00:34:32,656 --> 00:34:34,867
Actually, no...

411
00:34:36,618 --> 00:34:37,618
technically.

412
00:34:37,619 --> 00:34:39,870
- So, we're not together.
- Ah.

413
00:34:39,871 --> 00:34:42,541
So... Well, no, it's not
that we're not together.

414
00:34:43,166 --> 00:34:44,375
It's...

415
00:34:44,376 --> 00:34:45,543
Complicated.

416
00:34:46,712 --> 00:34:48,588
[chuckles] Yeah.

417
00:34:48,589 --> 00:34:50,046
[stammers]

418
00:34:50,047 --> 00:34:53,467
Hey, would you grab a
coffee with me or something?

419
00:34:54,928 --> 00:34:58,890
Ah, well, I'm kind of
stuck here all day.

420
00:34:58,891 --> 00:35:03,896
Okay. Or, you know, like,
after y-you get off, or...

421
00:35:05,606 --> 00:35:08,859
Or... This is... That's
you letting me down easy.

422
00:35:09,526 --> 00:35:10,694
[stammers]

423
00:35:11,862 --> 00:35:13,113
- I'm sorry.
- Sorry.

424
00:35:15,199 --> 00:35:18,744
Yeah. Fuck. Fuck, sorry.

425
00:35:19,411 --> 00:35:21,537
All good. Thanks for coming in.

426
00:35:21,538 --> 00:35:23,332
Thank you. Thank you.

427
00:35:28,086 --> 00:35:30,339
Hi. Can I help you?

428
00:35:40,432 --> 00:35:42,476
[laughs] You're dressed.

429
00:35:56,823 --> 00:35:58,367
[speaks indistinctly]

430
00:36:01,203 --> 00:36:02,246
Great.

431
00:36:11,046 --> 00:36:12,381
Tickle time, tickle time.

432
00:36:24,476 --> 00:36:25,686
[Amanda] Not your world?

433
00:36:34,319 --> 00:36:36,321
Soon we'll be out of ampoules

434
00:36:37,865 --> 00:36:38,949
and options.

435
00:36:42,870 --> 00:36:43,871
Yeah.

436
00:37:04,308 --> 00:37:05,475
May I?

437
00:37:11,982 --> 00:37:13,066
Thank you.

438
00:37:21,366 --> 00:37:22,451
Um...

439
00:37:24,369 --> 00:37:28,707
You're writing about her hair
length, color, job description.

440
00:37:30,709 --> 00:37:32,126
I don't think it's enough.

441
00:37:32,127 --> 00:37:34,963
- I'm doing the best that I can.
- I know you are,

442
00:37:36,632 --> 00:37:38,300
but I think you
need to go deeper.

443
00:37:40,302 --> 00:37:41,303
Yeah.

444
00:37:42,554 --> 00:37:44,139
[exhales deeply]

445
00:37:47,643 --> 00:37:49,520
I think I need to get some air.

446
00:37:50,646 --> 00:37:52,898
Bring us some food or something.
I'll be... I'll be back.

447
00:37:54,942 --> 00:37:56,401
[thunder rumbling]

448
00:37:59,905 --> 00:38:03,367
[door opens, closes]

449
00:38:07,996 --> 00:38:08,996
[sighs]

450
00:39:06,847 --> 00:39:10,350
Yeah, last name
Dessen. D-E-S-S-E-N.

451
00:39:11,268 --> 00:39:13,562
- Okay. Thank you.
- [knocking]

452
00:39:20,777 --> 00:39:21,820
Hey.

453
00:39:28,285 --> 00:39:29,745
Thought you'd left me.

454
00:39:31,538 --> 00:39:34,291
Sorry. I... I promise I
would never leave you.

455
00:39:35,459 --> 00:39:36,919
Where have you been?

456
00:39:38,670 --> 00:39:43,467
I've been watching
myself, following myself.

457
00:39:44,259 --> 00:39:49,555
Followed Daniela and I to a restaurant,
sat outside the window just watching.

458
00:39:49,556 --> 00:39:51,225
Then they went to a movie.

459
00:39:52,476 --> 00:39:55,311
I went to the theater, I
sat behind them up the back,

460
00:39:55,312 --> 00:39:57,898
watching them watch a fucking
movie. [breathes shakily]

461
00:39:59,107 --> 00:40:04,320
And I started to understand how
your Jason did what he did to me.

462
00:40:04,321 --> 00:40:06,532
He must have watched
me for fucking weeks.

463
00:40:07,533 --> 00:40:11,203
At work, followed me and
Daniela to date night,

464
00:40:11,787 --> 00:40:14,914
watching us through the window, moving
through the house at fucking night,

465
00:40:14,915 --> 00:40:19,001
imagining me gone,
imagining me fucking gone.

466
00:40:19,002 --> 00:40:23,131
I'm... [stammers] I'm having some
fucking crazy thoughts right now.

467
00:40:25,634 --> 00:40:27,134
This isn't working.

468
00:40:27,135 --> 00:40:28,262
Yeah.

469
00:40:29,096 --> 00:40:30,304
We're spinning our wheels.

470
00:40:30,305 --> 00:40:32,098
Yeah, but, you see,
we're getting closer.

471
00:40:32,099 --> 00:40:33,891
- Oh, Jason.
- So... Don't... No, no.

472
00:40:33,892 --> 00:40:37,771
Think about where we started,
and we're getting so much closer.

473
00:40:38,355 --> 00:40:40,148
The world you're looking for...

474
00:40:42,109 --> 00:40:44,735
is a grain of sand
on an infinite beach.

475
00:40:44,736 --> 00:40:46,904
No, don't you... don't say that.

476
00:40:46,905 --> 00:40:49,616
Jason. Jason.

477
00:40:51,243 --> 00:40:53,036
You've seen your wife murdered.

478
00:40:53,704 --> 00:40:56,664
You've seen her die
of a horrible disease.

479
00:40:56,665 --> 00:40:58,375
Seen her not recognize you.

480
00:40:58,959 --> 00:41:01,419
Married to other men. Married
to other versions of you.

481
00:41:01,420 --> 00:41:02,753
[sniffs]

482
00:41:02,754 --> 00:41:05,716
Our brains weren't
built for that, okay?

483
00:41:07,009 --> 00:41:09,093
How much more of
this can you take?

484
00:41:09,094 --> 00:41:14,056
No, it doesn't matter how much I can or
can't take, it's about finding my Daniela.

485
00:41:14,057 --> 00:41:16,809
We have ten ampoules left.

486
00:41:16,810 --> 00:41:17,895
Ten.

487
00:41:23,275 --> 00:41:24,358
Maybe you're right.

488
00:41:24,359 --> 00:41:27,905
- It is fucking impossible.
- It's not. Look at me. It's not.

489
00:41:29,489 --> 00:41:31,408
I'm not asking you
to give up hope.

490
00:41:32,284 --> 00:41:34,745
All I'm saying is that we need
to try something different.

491
00:41:36,413 --> 00:41:37,831
[sighs]

492
00:41:42,336 --> 00:41:44,129
[Amanda] I understand
why she's mad.

493
00:41:44,755 --> 00:41:48,258
It's her choice if and when she
ever shows her art to anyone.

494
00:41:49,051 --> 00:41:50,802
That's just what she said.

495
00:41:51,845 --> 00:41:53,221
What are you feeling right now?

496
00:41:53,222 --> 00:41:54,514
[inhales deeply]

497
00:41:54,515 --> 00:41:59,186
Honestly, like I wanna leave.

498
00:42:00,312 --> 00:42:01,647
Because of this fight?

499
00:42:02,439 --> 00:42:04,358
Well, because of everything.

500
00:42:05,067 --> 00:42:10,947
I worked my ass off to get here,
and it's just all turning to shit.

501
00:42:10,948 --> 00:42:12,199
[smacks lips]

502
00:42:13,408 --> 00:42:15,953
What do you think about when
you think about leaving?

503
00:42:20,165 --> 00:42:24,169
A corridor, infinitely long,

504
00:42:25,128 --> 00:42:30,676
with all these doors, evenly
spaced, as far as the eye can see.

505
00:42:32,052 --> 00:42:36,556
And behind each one of these
doors is a version of my life

506
00:42:36,557 --> 00:42:38,350
that I could have lived.

507
00:42:40,018 --> 00:42:45,606
If I don't like the version I'm in,
I can just walk through another door.

508
00:42:45,607 --> 00:42:47,818
That's an interesting metaphor.

509
00:42:49,361 --> 00:42:50,445
Might have to steal it.

510
00:42:51,864 --> 00:42:52,948
It's all yours.

511
00:42:53,615 --> 00:42:55,701
You talk about all these doors,

512
00:42:56,827 --> 00:42:59,453
and maybe that's where
you feel most comfortable,

513
00:42:59,454 --> 00:43:01,248
living in a corridor.

514
00:43:03,417 --> 00:43:05,127
Know what another
name for that is?

515
00:43:06,253 --> 00:43:07,336
What?

516
00:43:07,337 --> 00:43:08,630
Fear of commitment.

517
00:43:09,548 --> 00:43:12,467
I have been married
for 15 years.

518
00:43:14,136 --> 00:43:16,180
You don't talk like
someone who has.

519
00:43:28,775 --> 00:43:29,902
Hey.

520
00:43:30,903 --> 00:43:33,113
- Hey.
- Did you think I wouldn't find out, man?

521
00:43:34,781 --> 00:43:36,992
- What are you talking about?
- Come on.

522
00:43:40,204 --> 00:43:43,484
Is that why you didn't wanna work with me,
'cause you're too busy stealing my shit?

523
00:43:44,750 --> 00:43:46,585
I didn't steal this from you.

524
00:43:47,252 --> 00:43:51,797
How could you have created
this? This compound?

525
00:43:51,798 --> 00:43:56,511
Jay, it's like you... you
looked inside my brain.

526
00:43:56,512 --> 00:44:02,512
Ryan, I swear to you, I haven't
been anywhere near your research.

527
00:44:10,526 --> 00:44:13,612
What about somebody
that works for you?

528
00:44:14,738 --> 00:44:15,739
No.

529
00:44:16,323 --> 00:44:17,907
You know when the
lawyers get involved,

530
00:44:17,908 --> 00:44:20,701
they are gonna comb through every facet
of your life, all your work product,

531
00:44:20,702 --> 00:44:22,703
your labs, anything
you've touched.

532
00:44:22,704 --> 00:44:24,539
Doesn't have to
come to that, Ryan.

533
00:44:24,540 --> 00:44:30,211
Jason, I am in prenegotiations with
multiple pharmaceutical companies.

534
00:44:30,212 --> 00:44:32,506
If they find out there's
competing biotech,

535
00:44:33,090 --> 00:44:34,424
it's all over.

536
00:44:35,551 --> 00:44:36,969
Who gave you my ampoule?

537
00:44:37,594 --> 00:44:38,595
Why does that matter?

538
00:44:41,682 --> 00:44:43,350
Does your compound work?

539
00:44:46,478 --> 00:44:47,646
We are so close.

540
00:44:50,941 --> 00:44:52,526
Well, what's your application?

541
00:44:55,237 --> 00:44:57,656
Safer alternative to
general anesthesia.

542
00:44:58,574 --> 00:45:01,326
Therapy for trauma.
Therapy for phobias.

543
00:45:01,827 --> 00:45:05,288
A whole new way of thinking
about pain management.

544
00:45:05,289 --> 00:45:06,707
Does yours work?

545
00:45:07,749 --> 00:45:10,419
Yeah, it does. It works.

546
00:45:12,212 --> 00:45:13,589
[sighs]

547
00:45:15,257 --> 00:45:16,258
Wow.

548
00:45:18,177 --> 00:45:19,928
How'd you target
the Brodmann areas?

549
00:45:22,931 --> 00:45:24,599
I can't say.

550
00:45:24,600 --> 00:45:25,767
Come on.

551
00:45:28,228 --> 00:45:29,229
Okay.

552
00:45:30,898 --> 00:45:33,692
Can you at least tell me
what your application is?

553
00:45:36,695 --> 00:45:37,863
[sighs]

554
00:45:43,660 --> 00:45:44,703
How about this?

555
00:45:47,664 --> 00:45:49,166
Why don't I just show you?

556
00:45:54,004 --> 00:45:55,172
What the fuck is that?

557
00:45:56,715 --> 00:45:58,133
That's my secret project.

558
00:45:59,510 --> 00:46:00,552
What's it for?

559
00:46:03,972 --> 00:46:05,182
I'm about to show you.

560
00:46:20,072 --> 00:46:21,949
[injector beeps, clicks]

561
00:46:25,327 --> 00:46:26,662
Holy shit, Jay.

562
00:46:31,500 --> 00:46:34,752
Wait, you want... you want me
to put that in my veins too?

563
00:46:34,753 --> 00:46:36,337
Only if you wanna
know how it works.

564
00:46:36,338 --> 00:46:37,840
Is it safe?

565
00:46:40,467 --> 00:46:42,761
Yeah. I've done it
over a hundred times.

566
00:46:54,356 --> 00:46:55,356
Okay.

567
00:47:16,253 --> 00:47:17,629
[laughs]

568
00:47:19,214 --> 00:47:23,134
I don't understand what I'm
seeing. Jay, what is this?

569
00:47:23,135 --> 00:47:27,054
Well, this is a
manifestation of your mind

570
00:47:27,055 --> 00:47:32,311
as it tries to visually explain something
our brains haven't evolved to comprehend.

571
00:47:33,187 --> 00:47:34,605
Which is what?

572
00:47:35,606 --> 00:47:39,109
A five-dimensional
probability space,

573
00:47:40,068 --> 00:47:43,363
also known as superposition.

574
00:47:45,699 --> 00:47:46,700
Jay...

575
00:47:48,911 --> 00:47:51,413
are you saying I'm in a
quantum state right now?

576
00:47:52,247 --> 00:47:55,500
- Yeah. Yeah.
- [breathes shakily] Jay.

577
00:47:55,501 --> 00:47:57,586
Now, it looks like a corridor,

578
00:47:58,670 --> 00:48:02,798
but it's actually the box repeating
itself across all possible realities

579
00:48:02,799 --> 00:48:07,345
that share the same
coordinates of space and time.

580
00:48:07,346 --> 00:48:08,680
This can't be...

581
00:48:12,142 --> 00:48:13,268
This is real.

582
00:48:14,102 --> 00:48:15,187
Jason.

583
00:48:16,813 --> 00:48:17,898
Oh, my...

584
00:48:19,149 --> 00:48:20,650
What's behind the doors?

585
00:48:20,651 --> 00:48:23,820
An infinite amount of variations
of the world you know.

586
00:48:24,530 --> 00:48:27,366
Some subtly different and some
that'll blow your fucking mind.

587
00:48:31,870 --> 00:48:33,454
Fuck.

588
00:48:33,455 --> 00:48:35,248
- Wait, wait. No.
- What?

589
00:48:35,249 --> 00:48:36,333
This...

590
00:48:37,626 --> 00:48:39,294
Okay, this is the
dangerous part.

591
00:48:40,379 --> 00:48:43,130
Aspects of your consciousness,
like your emotional state...

592
00:48:43,131 --> 00:48:44,131
Okay.

593
00:48:44,132 --> 00:48:47,678
determine which reality we
find when we open a door.

594
00:48:49,263 --> 00:48:53,140
- Oh. Fuck. Of course we do...
- So, all I need you to do is concentrate.

595
00:48:53,141 --> 00:48:55,226
- I know you're excited...
- [inhales deeply] I'm trying, buddy.

596
00:48:55,227 --> 00:48:56,394
I'm trying. Okay.

597
00:48:56,395 --> 00:48:59,772
- Breathe in.
- [clears throat, inhales deeply]

598
00:48:59,773 --> 00:49:02,442
- And out.
- [exhales deeply]

599
00:49:03,777 --> 00:49:04,820
Ready?

600
00:49:34,266 --> 00:49:35,601
This is Chicago?

601
00:49:36,727 --> 00:49:38,478
It's a different
version of Chicago.

602
00:49:40,564 --> 00:49:44,108
It's a kinder and more
progressive place than our world.

603
00:49:44,109 --> 00:49:46,528
[inhales deeply, gasps]

604
00:49:50,199 --> 00:49:53,410
Okay, so why... Ho...
How did we end up here?

605
00:49:54,828 --> 00:49:58,457
I just thought of the kind of place
that my friend would like to see.

606
00:50:02,419 --> 00:50:03,462
[gasps]

607
00:50:04,963 --> 00:50:07,257
Oh, there are so many
things I could show you.

608
00:50:09,676 --> 00:50:13,054
[breathes shakily,
exhales deeply]

609
00:50:13,055 --> 00:50:14,139
[Jason chuckles]

610
00:50:15,307 --> 00:50:18,685
We... We can't stay long.

611
00:50:19,478 --> 00:50:22,271
You give me your phone,
I'll... I'll take a picture.

612
00:50:22,272 --> 00:50:23,774
[breathes shakily] Yeah.

613
00:50:28,445 --> 00:50:30,989
[gasping]

614
00:50:38,038 --> 00:50:42,459
Jason, I can't believe you
built a better compound than me.

615
00:50:43,001 --> 00:50:44,503
[shutter clicks]

616
00:50:46,129 --> 00:50:49,466
I really thought I was the only one in
the world with the know-how to make it.

617
00:50:50,634 --> 00:50:51,634
[breathes shakily]

618
00:50:51,635 --> 00:50:56,265
Well, there are many,
many, many worlds.

619
00:50:58,183 --> 00:50:59,434
[gasps]

620
00:51:02,312 --> 00:51:04,398
And there are many, many Ryans.

621
00:51:25,377 --> 00:51:27,462
You're not the Jason
I know, are you?

622
00:51:32,676 --> 00:51:33,677
Hey...

623
00:51:35,971 --> 00:51:39,641
I won't be a problem
for you, all right?

624
00:51:45,480 --> 00:51:49,359
No, wait. Wait. Wait. Wait!

625
00:51:51,153 --> 00:51:52,153
No, wait.

626
00:51:52,779 --> 00:51:56,073
[grunts, breathes heavily] Jay!

627
00:51:56,074 --> 00:51:57,910
[breathing heavily]

628
00:52:03,707 --> 00:52:06,793
[sighing]

629
00:52:07,419 --> 00:52:09,671
[phone vibrating]

630
00:52:47,501 --> 00:52:48,627
[person] Jason?

631
00:52:49,628 --> 00:52:50,962
Yeah, that's me.

632
00:52:50,963 --> 00:52:52,129
I'm Anthony.

633
00:52:52,130 --> 00:52:54,173
- Hey.
- I'm Leighton's guy.

634
00:52:54,174 --> 00:52:56,884
Yeah. Thanks for coming
on such short notice.

635
00:52:56,885 --> 00:52:59,303
- Think you'll be able to do that?
- [Anthony] Absolutely.

636
00:52:59,304 --> 00:53:02,265
What we'll do is, we'll
start out with framing it up.

637
00:53:02,266 --> 00:53:03,559
Get some guys...
